IssueDetail.Description:
We emit labels using a global static `Compiler::s_compMethodsCount` e.g.:
```
printf("G_M%03u_IG%02u" Compiler::s_compMethodsCount id->idAddr()->iiaIGlabel->igNum);
```

Thats dangerous if two JITs are running at the same time and generating JitDumps. We should change to using a Compiler member and then change:
```
#ifdef DEBUG
    /* Give the function a unique number */

    if (opts.disAsm || opts.dspEmit || verbose)
    {
        s_compMethodsCount = ~info.compMethodHash() & 0xffff;
    }
    else
    {
        s_compMethodsCount++;
    }
#endif
```
To:
```
#ifdef DEBUG
    /* Give the function a unique number */

    if (opts.disAsm || opts.dspEmit || verbose)
    {
        compMethodNumber = ~info.compMethodHash() & 0xffff;
    }
    else
    {
        compMethodNumber = s_compMethodsCount;
        s_compMethodsCount++;
    }
#endif
```
And the calls to:
```
printf("G_M%03u_IG%02u" compMethodNumber id->idAddr()->iiaIGlabel->igNum);
```

Some places we access `s_compMethodsCount` currently might not have a `Compiler` pointer so it might be a little more work than this.

category:implementation
theme:debug-dumps
skill-level:beginner
cost:small

IssueDetail.Title_Description:
Fix JitDump label output to be multi-thread safe We emit labels using a global static `Compiler::s_compMethodsCount` e.g.:
```
printf("G_M%03u_IG%02u" Compiler::s_compMethodsCount id->idAddr()->iiaIGlabel->igNum);
```

